ST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: apparently from Middle English  <i>boue</i> ‘bow, curve’ +  <i>yat</i> ‘gate’, applied as a place-name, but the place has not been identified."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Bowett was born in 1345, in Wrentham, Suffolk, England, his father, Thomas Bowet, was 18 and his mother, Mrs Thomas Bowet, was 15. He married Margaret le Brun. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died on 22 March 1420, in Langley, Norfolk, England, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1345–22 March 1420":"1345–22. märts 1420","1345–1420":"1345–1420","1352–Female":"1352–Surnud","1373–1421":"1373–1421","1375–1421":"1375–1421","1379–Male":"1379–Surnud","1327–1372":"1327–1372","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1373":"1373","1372":"1372","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1327":"1327","1379":"1379","1345":"1345","1421":"1421","1420":"1420","1375":"137